<!-- DEEP 1 -->
<section>
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="prose">
      <span class="eyebrow">★ The income most lenders undercount</span>
      <h3 style="margin-top:14px;">BAH, BAS, and the "gross-up" most lenders never apply.</h3>
      <p>Here's a problem we see every week. A soldier brings in a Leave and Earnings Statement showing solid total compensation, applies with a big-box lender, and gets approved for far less than the numbers should allow. Why? Because the lender only counted base pay and quietly ignored the allowances — the very money designed to pay for housing.</p>
      <p>Basic Allowance for Housing (BAH) and Basic Allowance for Subsistence (BAS) are not taxed. That's not a loophole; it's how military compensation is structured, and it's spelled out plainly in the <a href="https://militarypay.defense.gov/Pay/Allowances/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Department of Defense pay and allowances guidance</a>. Because that income is tax-free, lending guidelines let us "gross it up" — adjusting it upward to reflect its true value next to taxable civilian income. On a typical soldier's BAH, that adjustment can add meaningful qualifying power, often translating to tens of thousands of dollars more home you can afford. The exact figure depends on your pay grade, dependents, and duty-station rate, which you can verify on the <a href="https://www.travel.dod.mil/Allowances/Basic-Allowance-for-Housing/BAH-Rate-Lookup/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">official DTMO BAH rate lookup</a>.</p>
      <p>Our army mortgage programs are built to count this correctly the first time. We read your LES the way a fellow service member would, document BAH and BAS to the standard underwriting requires, and make sure none of your hard-earned compensation gets left on the table. For active-duty soldiers receiving BAH, this single step is frequently the difference between qualifying for a starter condo and qualifying for the home your family actually needs.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- DEEP 2 -->
<section class="band-2">
